<hw>-wards</hw>
<pr>(w⟦etil⟧rdz)</pr> }</mhw>. <ety>[AS. <ets>-weard</ets>,
<ets>-weardes</ets>; akin to OS. & OFries. <ets>-ward</ets>. OHG.
<ets>-wert</ets>, G. <ets>-w⟦aum⟧rts</ets>, Icel. <ets>-ver⟦edh⟧r</ets>,
Goth. <ets>-va⟦iacute⟧r⟦thorn⟧s</ets>, L. <ets>vertere</ets> to turn,
<ets>versus</ets> toward, and E. <ets>worth</ets> to become. ⟦root⟧143.
See <er>Worth</er>. <pos>v. i.</pos>, and cf. <er>Verse</er>. Adverbs
ending in <ets>-wards</ets> (AS. <ets>-weardes</ets>) and some other
adverbs, such as <ets>besides</ets>, <ets>betimes</ets>,
<ets>since</ets> (OE. <ets>sithens</ets>). etc., were originally
genitive forms used adverbially.]</ety> <def>Suffixes denoting
